==Proto-Indo-European==

===Etymology===
The word {{m|ine-pro||*wÄºÌ¥kÊ·os}} is a thematic accented zero-grade noun perhaps derived from the adjective {{m|ine-pro|*wlÌ¥kÊ·Ã³s|t=dangerous}}; compare {{cog|hit|ğ’‰¿ğ’€ ğ’†ªğ’‰¿ğ’€¸|tr=walkuwa-|t=something negative}}, {{cog|sga|olc|t=evil}}, {{cog|sa|à¤…à¤µà¥ƒà¤•|tr=avá¹›kÃ¡|t=safe|lit=not wild}}, {{m|sa|à¤µà¥ƒà¤•à¤¤à¤¾à¤¤à¥|tr=vá¹›kÃ¡-tÄt|t=savagery}}.<ref>A. Lehrman, â€œAnatolian Cognates of the PIE Word for â€˜Wolfâ€™â€, ''Die Sprache'' 33 (1987), 13â€“18.</ref> Stress shift onto the zero-grade is consistent with nominalized adjectives: compare {{cog|sa|à¤•à¥ƒà¤·à¥à¤£|tr=ká¹›Ìá¹£á¹‡a|t=black antelope}} from {{m|sa|à¤•à¥ƒà¤·à¥à¤£|tr=ká¹›á¹£á¹‡Ã¡|t=black}}. Alternatively, the word may be a derivative of the verbal root {{m|ine-pro|*welhâ‚‚-|t=to tear up}}.<ref>Tamaz Gamkrelidze & VjaÄeslav Ivanov, ''Indo-European and the Indo-Europeans'' (Tbilisi: Tbilisi UP, 1984), 492.</ref> In either case, the word's formation closely resembles that of {{m|ine-pro|*hâ‚‚Å•Ì¥tá¸±os|t=bear}}, another thematic accented zero-grade noun whose referent is an animal subject to cultural taboos.<ref>{{R:ine:EIEC|head=*wolf|page=646}}</ref>

The Latin and Greek reflexes are unexpected (vs. expected Lat *''volquus'', Gk *''Ã¡lpos'', according to the regular progression PIE *''lÌ¥'' > Lat ''ol'', Gk ''al''). The Latin reflex is a borrowing from [[Osco-Umbrian]] (where PIE */kÊ·/ regularly gave /p/), and both the Italic and Greek reflexes underwent metathesis, possibly as a taboo deformation meant to offset the fear usually associated with the animal. A deformation would explain the metathesis of */w/ and */l/, which also occurred in Greek ({{m|ine-pro||*wÄºÌ¥kÊ·os}} â†’ {{m|ine-pro||*lÃºkÊ·os}} â†’ {{m|grc|Î»ÏÎºÎ¿Ï‚}}), and also explains the presence of delabialized /k/ per the [[w:boukÃ³los rule|''boukÃ³los'' rule]] (regardless of whether it is Proto-Indo-European already or only Proto-Greek). In both cases, the expected forms are so close to the word for â€œfoxâ€&nbsp;â€“ compare {{cog|la|volpÄ“s}}, {{cog|grc|á¼€Î»Ï‰Ï€ÏŒÏ‚}}, {{m|grc|á¼€Î»ÏÏ€Î·Î¾}}&nbsp;â€“ that avoiding conflation of the two words â€œwolfâ€ and â€œfoxâ€ may have motivated either alteration or borrowing.

The Germanic reflex, with /f/ < */p/ < */kÊ·/, underwent an unusual sound change, but the velar was retained in at least one form, i.&nbsp;e. {{cog|non|ylgr|t=she-wolf}} (vs. {{cog|ang|wylf}}, {{cog|gmh|wÃ¼lpe}} < {{m|gmw-pro|*wulbi}}) < {{m|gem-pro|*wulgÄ«|*wulgÊ·Ä«Ì}} < {{m|ine-pro|*wlÌ¥kÊ·Ã­hâ‚‚s}}.

Armenian and Celtic have replaced the word with {{noncog|ine-pro|*waylos|t=howler}} due to taboo; compare {{cog|xcl|Õ£Õ¡ÕµÕ¬}}, {{cog|mga|fÃ¡el}}.<ref>{{R:xcl:Martirosyan|page=196}}.</ref> (In Celtic, {{m|cel-pro|*kÅ«|t=hound, dog}} is also used to designate the wolf.)

