From {{inh|en|enm|fyr}}, from {{inh|en|ang|fÈ³r|t=fire}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*fuir}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*fuÃ¯r}}, a regularised form of {{inh|en|gem-pro|*fÅr|t=fire}} (compare {{cog|stq|Fjuur}}, {{cog|fy|fjoer}}, {{cog|nl|vuur}}, {{cog|nds|FÃ¼er}}, {{cog|de|Feuer}}, {{cog|da|fyr}}), ultimately from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*pÃ©hâ‚‚wrÌ¥}}.

Compare {{cog|hit|ğ’‰ºğ’„´ğ’„¯|tr=paá¸«á¸«ur}}, {{cog|xum|pir}}, {{w|Tocharian}} A/B {{m|xto|por}}/{{m|txb|puwar}}, {{cog|cs|pÃ½Å™|t=hot ashes}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|Ï€á¿¦Ï|t=fire}}, and {{cog|hy|Õ°Õ¸Ö‚Ö€|t=fire}}). This was an inanimate noun whose animate counterpart was {{cog|ine-pro|*hâ‚nÌ¥gÊ·nis}} (see ''[[ignite]]''). Cognate to {{doublet|notext=1|en|pyre}}.

