====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To set (something, often a building) [[on fire]].
#* {{RQ:Wells Invisible Man|chapter=At the House in Great Portland Street|page=186|passage=["]Then I slipped up again with a box of matches, '''fired''' my heap of paper and rubbish, put the chairs and bedding thereby, led the gas to the affair, by means of an india-rubber tube, and waving a farewell to the room left it for the last time." / "You '''fired''' the house!" exclaimed Kemp. / "'''Fired''' the house. It was the only way to cover my trail&nbsp;â€“ and no doubt it was insured.["]}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1887|author=H. Rider Haggard|authorlink=H. Rider Haggard|title=She: A History of Adventure|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/3155/3155-0.txt|passage=That lamp was the mummy of a woman tied to a stout stake let into the rock, and he had '''fired''' her hair.}}
#* {{RQ:London Iron Heel|passage=It was long a question of debate, whether the burning of the South Side ghetto was accidental, or whether it was done by the Mercenaries; but it is definitely settled now that the ghetto was '''fired''' by the Mercenaries under orders from their chiefs.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To heat as with [[#Noun|fire]], but without setting [[on fire]], as [[ceramic]], metal objects, etc.
#: {{ux|en|If you '''fire''' the pottery at too high a temperature, it may crack.}}
#: {{ux|en|They '''fire''' the wood to make it easier to put a point on the end.}}
#* {{RQ:Ferguson Zollenstein|IV}}
#*: So this was my future home, I thought! Certainly it made a brave picture. I had seen similar ones '''fired'''-in on many a Heidelberg stein. Backed by towering hills,{{...}}a sky of palest Gobelin flecked with fat, fleecy little clouds, it in truth looked a dear little city; the city of one's dreams.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To drive away by setting a [[#Noun|fire]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Sonnets|sonnet=144|passage=Till my bad angel '''fire''' my good one out.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[terminate]] the [[employment]] contract of (an employee), especially [[for cause]] (such as [[misconduct]] or [[poor]] [[performance]]).
#: {{ant|en|hire}}
#* '''1969''', {{w|Vladimir Nabokov}}, ''{{w|Ada or Ardor: A Family Chronicle|Ada or Ardor}}'', Penguin 2011, p.226:
#*: The first, obvious choice was hysterical and fantastic Blanche â€“ had there not been her timidity, her fear of being â€˜'''fired'''â€™{{nb...}}.
# {{lb|en|transitive|by extension}} To terminate a [[contract]] with a [[client]]; to [[drop]] a client.
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1979|author=Richard Collins Rea|title=Operating a Successful Accounting Practice: A Collection of Material from the Journal of Accountancy Practitioners Forum|chapter=|url=|page=288|isbn=9780608150970|oclc=122394178|text=Don't be hesitant to '''fire''' a client - cull out the deadwood. If a client doesn't meet the above criteria, you are better off without him. You don't do your best work for a client you'd rather not have.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=2020|author=Rebecca Migdal|title=Museum Mercenary: A Handbook for Independent Museum Professionals|chapter=|url=|page=278|isbn=9781538118603|oclc=1202618438|text=Maintaining a collegial attitude even when doing the more difficult business work, like '''firing''' a client, is another part. If you are struggling through the relationship, the client might be struggling as well, so '''firing''' them may be mutually beneficial, and you should try and do it on the best of terms.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[shoot]] (a [[gun]], [[rocket]]/[[missile]], or analogous device).
#: {{ux|en|We will '''fire''' our guns at the enemy.}}
#: {{ux|en|The jet '''fired''' a salvo of rockets at the truck convoy.}}
#: {{ux|en|He '''fired''' his radar gun at passing cars.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[shoot]] a [[gun]], [[cannon]], or similar [[weapon]].
#: {{syn|en|open fire|shoot}}
#: {{ux|en|Don't '''fire''' until you see the whites of their eyes.}}
# {{lb|en|rocketry}} To operate a [[rocket]] [[engine]] to produce [[thrust]].
#: {{ux|en|The RCS thrusters '''fired''' several times to stabilize the tumbling spacecraft.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|mining}} To [[set off]] an [[explosive]] in a [[mine]].
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1887|author=H. Rider Haggard|authorlink=H. Rider Haggard|title=She: A History of Adventure|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/3155/3155-0.txt|passage=`Now are you both ready?' I said, as people do when they are going to '''fire''' a mine.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|sports}} To [[shoot]]; to attempt to [[score]] a [[goal]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 29, 2010|author=Mark Vesty|work=BBC
|title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9322845.stm Wigan 2-2 Arsenal]
|passage={{w|Andrey Arshavin}} equalised with a superb volley into the corner before {{w|Nicklas Bendtner}} coolly '''fired''' Arsenal in front.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|physiology}} To cause an [[action potential]] in a cell.
#: {{ux|en|When a neuron '''fires''', it transmits information.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[forcibly]] [[direct]] (something).
#: {{ux|en|He answered the questions the reporters '''fired''' at him.}}
# {{lb|en|ambitransitive|computer sciences, software engineering}} To [[initiate]] an [[event]] (by means of an [[event handler]]).
#: {{ux|en|The event handler should only '''fire''' after all web page content has finished loading.}}
#: {{ux|en|The queue '''fires''' a job whenever the thread pool is ready to handle it.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[inflame]]; to [[irritate]], as the passions.
#: {{ux|en|to '''fire''' the soul with anger, pride, or revenge}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|dated}} To be [[irritate]]d or [[inflame]]d with [[passion]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1864|author=Joseph Sheridan Le Fanu|title={{w|Uncle Silas}}|passage=Inexperienced girl as I was, I '''fired''' at the idea of becoming his dupe, and fancying, perhaps, that there was more in merely answering his note than it would have amounted to, I said â€” "That kind of thing may answer very well with button-makers, but ladies don't like it. {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Dryden Fables|Cymon and Iphigenia}}
#*: Love had '''fired''' my mind.
# To [[animate]]; to give [[life]] or [[spirit]] to.
#: {{ux|en|to '''fire''' the genius of a young man}}
# To [[feed]] or [[serve]] the [[#Noun|fire]] of.
#: {{ux|en|to '''fire''' a boiler}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1961|month=March|author=""Balmore""|title=Driving and firing modern French steam locomotives|journal=Trains Illustrated|pages=150, 151|text=We left with the "Blue Train", dead on time. This time I '''fired''' all the way. {{...}} The next day took me home again on No. E.16 with Henri Dutertre. I '''fired''' from Paris to Calais.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[light up]] as if by [[#Noun|fire]]; to [[illuminate]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Richard 3|III|ii|passage=[The sun] '''fires''' the proud tops of the eastern pines.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|farriery}} To [[cauterize]].
# {{lb|en|intransitive|dated}} To [[catch fire]]; to be [[kindle]]d.

