From {{suf|ine-pro|*dÊ°eÇµÊ°-|*Åm}}.

However, Kloekhorst argues that the Sanskrit and Anatolian evidence point towards a reconstruction of the root {{m|ine-pro|*dÊ°eÇµ-}} as opposed to ''*dÊ°eÇµÊ°-'' on the basis that:
# In the Sanskrit oblique stem jm-, -j- must reflect *Çµ-, and cannot reflect *ÇµÊ°-, which would regularly give -h- in all positions.
# The long vowel in the Hittite nom. sg. [tÄ“kan] suggests a "voiced unaspirated" (pre-glottalised) velar. See [http://www.kloekhorst.nl/KloekhorstPleneE.pdf Kloekhorst (2012)].
# The *ÇµÊ°- reconstructable from Latin, Germanic and Greek can be explained in the glottalic theory as a simplification of the cluster *dÊ°Çµ /dË€É¡/ to *dÊ°ÇµÊ° /dÉ¡/. The opposite development is much less likely. <br />

It should be noted, however, that the glottalic theory is not generally accepted.

A phonetically difficult but possible connection is with {{m|ine-pro|*(s)teg-|*(s)teÇµ-|to cover}}, with devoicing of ''*dÊ°'' to ''*t'' via {{w|Siebs' law}}.<ref>{{R:ine:Kortlandt:2014}}</ref>

