From {{inh|en|enm|feden}}, from {{inh|en|ang|fÄ“dan||to feed}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*fÅdijan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*fÅdijanÄ…||to feed}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*pehâ‚‚-||to guard, graze, feed}}. Cognate with {{cog|fy|fiede||to nourish, feed}}, {{cog|nl|voeden||to feed}}, {{cog|da|fÃ¸de||to bring forth, feed}}, {{cog|sv|fÃ¶da||to bring forth, feed}}, {{cog|is|fÃ¦Ã°a||to feed}}, and more distantly with {{cog|la|pÄscÅ||feed, nourish|pos=verb}} through Indo-European. More at {{l|en|food}}, {{l|en|fodder}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|+|+|fed}}

# {{lb|en|ditransitive}} To give (someone or something) [[food]] to [[eat]].
#: {{ux|en|'''Feed''' the dog every evening.}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|Romans|12|20}}
#*: If thine enemy hunger, '''feed''' him.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[eat]] {{qualifier|usually of animals}}.
#: {{ux|en|Spiders '''feed''' on gnats and flies.}}
#* {{RQ:Jefferies Amateur Poacher|chapter=1|passage=But then I had the [massive] flintlock by me for protection. Â¶{{...}}The linen-press and a chest on the top of it formed, however, a very good gun-carriage; and, thus mounted, aim could be taken out of the window at the old mare '''feeding''' in the meadow below by the brook, and a 'bead' could be drawn upon Molly, the dairymaid, kissing the fogger behind the hedge,{{nb...}}.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Book of Sharks|author={{w|Richard Ellis (biologist)|Richard Ellis}}| year=1983| publisher=Knopf| ISBN=0679722106| passage=While '''feeding''', the basking shark swims at about two knots per hour, and this enables it to eat and breathe in the same motion.|page=89}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give (someone or something) to (someone or something else) as food.
#: {{ux|en|'''Feed''' the fish to the dolphins.}}
#* '''2012''' December 25 (airdate), {{w|Steven Moffat}}, ''The Snowmen'' (''Doctor Who'')
#*: D<small>R</small> S<small>IMEON</small>: I said I'd '''feed''' you. I didn't say who to.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give to a [[machine]] to be [[process]]ed.
#: {{ux|en|'''Feed''' the paper gently into the document shredder.}}
#: {{ux|en|We got interesting results after '''feeding''' the computer with the new data.}}
# {{lb|en|figurative}} To satisfy, gratify, or minister to (a sense, taste, desire, etc.).
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|I|iii|text=If I can catch him once upon the hip, / I will '''feed''' fat the ancient grudge I bear him.}}
#* {{RQ:Knolles Turkes}}
#*: {{quote|en|'''feeding''' him with the hope of liberty}}
# To supply with something.
#: {{ux|en|Springs '''feed''' ponds with water.}}
# To [[graze]]; to cause to be [[crop]]ped by feeding, as [[herbage]] by [[cattle]].
#: {{ux|en|If grain is too forward in autumn, '''feed''' it with sheep.}}
#* {{RQ:Mortimer Husbandry|text=Once in three years, or every other year, '''feed''' your mowing-lands.}}
# {{lb|en|sports|transitive}} To [[pass]] to.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 28, 2010|author=Kevin Darlin|work=BBC| title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9308862.stm West Brom 1-3 Blackburn]| passage={{w|Ravel Morrison|Morrison}}  then played a pivotal role in West Brom's equaliser, powering through the middle and '''feeding''' {{w|Somen Tchoyi|Tchoyi}}, whose low, teasing right-wing cross was poked in by {{w|Jerome Thomas|Thomas}} at the far post}}
# {{lb|en|phonology|of a phonological rule}} To create the environment where another phonological rule can apply; to be applied before another rule.
#: {{ux|en|Nasalization '''feeds''' raising.}}
# {{lb|en|syntax|of a syntactic rule}} To create the syntactic environment in which another syntactic rule is applied; to be applied before another syntactic rule.
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Language|volume=59|issue=3| year=1983| title=Cliticization vs. Inflection: English N'T| author={{w|Arnold M. Zwicky}}| author2={{w|Geoffrey K. Pullum}}| jstor=413900| page=506<!-- of whole article: 502-513 -->| passage=This orthodox analysis {{...}} leads to the conclusion that {{...}} Subject&ndash;Auxiliary Inversion (SAI) is '''fed''' by the contraction operation.}}

