====Usage notes====
The declension of this noun was subject to a couple of minor variations:

* The inflected forms often featured an [[epenthetic]] /e/ before the /r/, especially in late Old English. For example, ''wÃ¦teres'' (gen. sg.) and ''wÃ¦tere'' (dat. sg.) might appear in place of expected ''wÃ¦tres'' and ''wÃ¦tre''. This reverses an earlier sound change from prehistoric Old English, where short /Ã¦/ and /e/ were regularly lost in word-internal open syllables when the preceding syllable was stressed.

* Similarly, the nominative/accusative plural varied between the expected form ''*wÃ¦ter'' and ''*wÃ¦t(e)ru''. The form with ''-u'' reverses another prehistoric sound change, where word-final /i/ and /u/ were lost following a [[w:syllable weight|heavy syllable]] or two light syllables. This makes ''wÃ¦ter'' part of a small class of neuter nouns which vary between the (expected) unchanged plural and an innovative plural ending in ''-u''. Other examples are ''wÇ£pn'' ~ ''wÇ£pnu'' (â€œweaponsâ€), ''tÄcn'' ~ ''tÄcnu'' (â€œsignsâ€), ''bÄ“acn'' ~ ''bÄ“acnu'' (â€œsignalsâ€), ''setl'' ~ ''setlu'' (â€œseatsâ€), ''leÄ¡er'' ~ ''leÄ¡ru'' (â€œcouchesâ€), ''wÄgrift'' ~ ''wÄgriftu'' (â€œcurtainsâ€), ''seÄ¡l'' ~ ''seÄ¡lu'' (â€œsailsâ€), ''botl'' ~ ''botlu'' (â€œdwellingsâ€), ''wolcn'' ~ ''wolcnu'' (â€œcloudsâ€), ''weder'' ~ ''wedru'' (â€œstormsâ€), ''brÃ¦Ä¡n'' ~ ''brÃ¦Ä¡nu'' (â€œbrainsâ€), ''wundor'' ~ ''wundru'' (â€œmiraclesâ€), ''tungol'' ~ ''tunglu'' (â€œstarsâ€), ''Ã¾È³rel'' ~ ''Ã¾È³rlu'' (â€holesâ€), and ''swefn'' ~ ''swefnu'' (â€œdreamsâ€).

