** Prefacing ''land'' with the genitive plural form of a people, producing the literal meaning â€œland of ____ people.â€ Ex: {{m|ang|Engla land|t=England|lit=land of the English}}, {{m|ang|Egypta land|t=Egypt|lit=land of the Egyptians}}, and {{m|ang|SiÄ¡elhearwena land|t=Ethiopia|lit=land of the Ethiopians}}.
* However, country names can also be formed other ways. For instance, words other than ''land'' are used: {{m|ang|Franca||a Frank}} â†’ {{m|ang|FrancrÄ«Ä‹e|t=France|lit=Frank kingdom}}, {{m|ang|Dene||a Dane}} â†’ {{m|ang|Denemearc|t=Denmark|lit=Dane borderland}}. It is also very common to use the name of a people for the country they inhabit: ''On Ã¾Äm dagum wÃ¦s Alexander Ä¡eboren on <u>CrÄ“cum</u> swÄ swÄ miÄ‹el È³st cÅme ofer ealne middanÄ¡eard'' (â€œIn those days, Alexander was born in <u>Greece</u> [lit. ''in the Greeks''] like a great storm coming over the whole worldâ€). In addition, country names are sometimes loaned directly from Latin: {{m|ang|Arabia}}, {{m|ang|IsrÄÄ“l}}, {{m|ang|Italia}}, {{m|ang|Syria}}. Finally, some country names are simply idiomatic: {{m|ang|NorÃ¾weÄ¡|t=Norway|lit=north way}}.
* Unlike most words, ''land'' undergoes {{w|i-umlaut}} when combined with the suffix {{m|ang|-isÄ‹}}: {{m|ang|inlendisÄ‹||native}}, {{m|ang|uplendisÄ‹||rural}}.

