** Even in many accents where this habitual syllable deletion is less usual, the syllable loss may still predominate for certain inflections that have become common words in their own right, such as {{m|en|gardener}} {{IPAchar|/É¡É‘Ë(É¹)d.nÉ™(É¹)/}}.
** Syllable loss may be habitually prevented to avoid merging with more deeply entrenched inflections, such as for keeping the generic inflection {{m|en|lightening}} {{IPAchar|/ËˆlaÉªt.nÌ©.ÉªÅ‹/}} from being pronounced identically to the established term {{m|en|lightning}} {{IPAchar|/ËˆlaÉªt.nÉªÅ‹/}} (notice the ''e'' is no longer written), even if they both independently derived from a combination of {{m|en|lighten}} + {{m|en|-ing}}.
*** But syllable loss may resume with inflections that are not in danger of merging with an established word, such as {{m|en|enlightening}}, which can be pronounced {{IPAchar|/É›nËˆlaÉªt.nÌ©.ÉªÅ‹/}} or {{IPAchar|/É›nËˆlaÉªt.nÉªÅ‹/}} because {{m|en|enlightning}} is not a common word outside of slang.

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|-n}}, {{m|enm|-en}}, past participle ending of [[strong verb]]s (compare {{cog|enm|[[take]](n), [[took]], [[taken]]||take, took, taken}}), from {{bor|en|non|-inn}}, past participle ending of strong verbs (compare {{cog|non|[[taka]], [[tÃ³k]], [[tekinn]]||take, took, taken}}). From {{der|en|gmq-pro|*-á›áš¾áš¨-||tr=*-ina-}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*-inaz}}, a variant of {{m|gem-pro|*-anaz}}. Replaced the native past participle ending of strong verbs (from {{cog|ang|-en}}) in some words, which had weakened to ''-e'' or disappeared (compare Southern {{cog|enm|[[do]](n), [[dud]](e), [[ydo]]||do, did, done}}), but not in others (compare {{m|enm|[[cume]](n), [[com]], [[ycume]]||come, came, come}}), from {{der|en|gem-pro|*-anaz}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*-nÃ³s}}.

