==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|AU|}} {{IPA|en|/É™ÊŠ/}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|en|/oÊŠ/}}
* {{homophones|en|o|owe|oh}}

===Etymology 1===
Perhaps from a special use of the interjection {{m|en|O}}, {{m|en|oh}}; and/or perhaps from {{m|en|o||one}}, from {{inh|en|enm|o}}, {{m|enm|oo}}, variant of {{m|en|a}}, {{m|enm|on}}, {{m|enm|oon}}, {{m|enm|an||one}}. See {{l|en|one}} and {{l|en|-y}}.

====Suffix====
{{head|en|suffix|plural|-os|or|-oes}}

# {{non-gloss definition|A [[colloquializing]] [[suffix]], [[typically]] [[append]]ed to [[name]]s, [[abbreviation]]s of [[long]] [[word]]s, or [[substantive]] [[use]]s of [[adjective]]s.}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|kid|kiddo}}
#: {{suffixusex|en|ugly|uggo}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Stephen Fry|authorlink=Stephen Fry|chapter=III|title=[[:w:The Liar (novel)|The Liar]]|location=London|publisher=[[w:Heinemann (publisher)|William Heinemann]]|year=1991|page=26|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/liar0000frys_j2c4/page/26/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-434-27191-7|passage=Adrian thought it worth while to try out his new slang. â€˜I say, you fellows, here's a rum go. Old Biff'''o''' was jolly odd this morning. He gave me a lot of pi-jaw about slacking and then invited me to tea. No rotting! He did really.â€™}}

=====Usage notes=====
''-o'' generally does not change the meaning of the word or name but only makes it more colloquial, as with {{m|en|cheapo}} and {{m|en|Jacko}}. It is often appended to [[clip]]ped or [[elide]]d forms of longer words, as with {{m|en|ambo}} and {{m|en|parmo}}. Occasionally, the terminal consonent of the clipped form is doubled for clarity of meaning or punctuation, as with {{m|en|uggo}} and {{m|en|doggo}}. It sometimes does change the meaning of words, usually by being applied to adjectives to indicate a person with a pronounced trait, as with {{m|en|weirdo||weird person}}, or to nouns used [[metonym]]ously to indicate a person with a pronounced connection to the other object, as with {{m|en|wino||poor or vagrant alcoholic}}. Especially in American English, some uses of this suffix are understood as dated slang, as with {{m|en|bucko}} and {{m|en|neato}}. The suffix is most frequently and widely encountered in Australian English, which has additional uses (such as {{m|en|rego}} for {{m|en|registration}} and {{m|en|nasho}} for {{m|en|national service}}) that are never or only extremely rarely encountered in other dialects.

Its meaning is very similar to some uses of {{m|en|-y}} and its use is particularly common where use of {{m|en|-y}} might cause misunderstanding, as with {{m|en|randy}} and {{m|en|rando}}, {{m|en|journey}} and {{m|en|journo}}, {{m|en|whiny}} and {{m|en|wino}}.

