====Reconstruction notes====
There is evidence for both [[suffixal]] and [[radical]] accent:
* Germanic {{m|gem-pro|*mÅdÄ“r}} ({{w|Verner's law}}) and Sanskrit {{m|sa|à¤®à¤¾à¤¤à¥ƒ|à¤®à¤¾à¤¤à¤¾|tr=mÄtÄÌ}} show accentuation on the suffix.
* Greek {{m|grc|Î¼Î®Ï„Î·Ï}} shows accentuation on the root.
* Balto-Slavic is inconclusive (the original accent could have been retracted to the root syllable by {{w|Hirt's law}}).
Only one of these can be the original accentuation, which means that the other must have undergone an analogical accent shift. PIE kinship terms that are semantically closest to â€œmotherâ€ are {{m|ine-pro|*phâ‚‚tá¸—r||father}} and {{m|ine-pro|*dÊ°ughâ‚‚tá¸—r||daughter}} and they show in their nominative singular forms accentuation of the suffix, which suggests that the word for â€œmotherâ€ was likely originally accented on the root, shifting its accent to the suffix in some languages under the influence of words for â€œdaughterâ€ and â€œfatherâ€.

The reconstruction of the declension paradigm is similarly problematic:
* Accusative singular forms are Sanskrit {{m|sa||à¤®à¤¾à¤¤à¤°à¤®à¥|tr=mÄtÃ¡ram}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|Î¼Î·Ï„Î­ÏÎ±}}, i.&nbsp;e. accented on the suffix only (Lithuanian {{m|lt|mÃ³terÄ¯}} has radical stress due to {{w|Hirt's law}}).
* Genitive singular forms include Sanskrit {{m|sa||à¤®à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=mÄtÃºá¸¥}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|Î¼Î·Ï„ÏÏŒÏ‚}}, i.&nbsp;e. accented only on the [[desinence]] (Lithuanian {{m|lt|mÃ³teres}} has radical stress due to {{w|Hirt's law}}).
From a strictly methodological point of view, this would point to a [[hysterokinetic]] inflection, with the reconstructed accusative singular {{m|ine-pro||*mehâ‚‚tÃ©rm}} and the genitive singular {{m|ine-pro||*mehâ‚‚trÃ©s}}. However, since the words for â€œfatherâ€ and â€œdaughterâ€ appear to have influenced the nominative singular form in some languages, it is possible that the same analogical process occurred in the accusative and genitive singular forms as well.

The conclusive evidence for the original [[acrostatic]] inflection is the Sanskrit ending for the genitive singular in the word {{m|sa||à¤®à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=mÄtÃºá¸¥}}, which is {{m|sa||-à¤‰à¤ƒ}}, the same ending used for other kinship terms: {{m|sa||à¤ªà¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=pitÃºá¸¥|father|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|sa||à¤¦à¥à¤¹à¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=duhitÃºá¸¥|daughter|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|sa||à¤­à¥à¤°à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=bhrÄÌtuá¸¥|brother|pos=gen. sg.}} etc. This ending can only reflect ''*-C-r-s'', with [[zero-grade]] of the suffix as well as of the ending, which is only possible in an acrostatic paradigm. A similar ending is found in Old Icelandic, where all kinship terms show the ending -or < PIE *-C-r-s, such as {{m|is|fÇ«Ã°or||father|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|is|mÃ³Ã°or||mother|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|is|brÃ³Ã°or||brother|pos=gen. sg.}}, {{m|is|dÃ³ttor||daughter|pos=gen. sg.}}. However, both in Sanskrit and in Old Icelandic this ending is found in ''all'' kinship terms, even in the ones that we know for sure ''not'' to have been acrostatically inflected like {{m|ine-pro|*phâ‚‚tá¸—r||father}} (genitive {{m|ine-pro||*phâ‚‚trÌ¥Ã©s}} >> Sanskrit {{m|sa||à¤ªà¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=pitÃºá¸¥}}, Old Icelandic {{m|is||fÇ«Ã°or}}) and {{m|ine-pro|*dÊ°ughâ‚‚tá¸—r||daughter}} (genitive {{m|ine-pro||*dÊ°ugtrÌ¥Ã©s}} >> Sanskrit {{m|sa||à¤¦à¥à¤¹à¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=duhitÃºá¸¥}}, Old Icelandic {{m|is||dÃ³ttor}}).

It follows that the ending must have spread from some other kinship term. Since PIE {{m|ine-pro|*bÊ°rÃ©hâ‚‚tÄ“r||brother}} must have been acrostatically inflected, the endings {{m|sa||-à¤‰à¤ƒ}} and ''-or'' must have been original in this word ({{m|ine-pro||*bÊ°rÃ©hâ‚‚trÌ¥s}} >> Sanskrit {{m|sa||à¤­à¥à¤°à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤ƒ|tr=bhrÄÌtuá¸¥}}, Old Icelandic {{m|is||brÃ³Ã°or}}). Since it appears unlikely that the ending {{m|ine-pro||*-r-s}} would have spread so vastly (even to the word for â€œfatherâ€) solely on the basis of the word for â€œbrotherâ€, we must assume that the ending was also present in another kinship term, namely the word for â€œmotherâ€, which was (as explained above) in its nominative singular form radically stressed, which would fit the acrostatic accentuation pattern, being the source of this genitive singular ending {{m|ine-pro||*-r-s}}.

