===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# True facts, genuine depiction or statements of reality.
#: {{ux|en|The '''truth''' is that our leaders knew a lot more than they were letting on.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1835|title=Specimens of the Table Talk of the late Samuel Taylor Coleridge|volume=II|author=Samuel Taylor Coleridge|coauthors={{w|Henry Nelson Coleridge}}|quotee={{w|Samuel Taylor Coleridge}}|isbn=9781986410328|url=https://books.google.com.sg/books/about/Specimens_of_the_Table_Talk_of_Samuel_Ta.html?id=csRVuAEACAAJ|page=19|pageurl=https://books.google.com.sg/books?id=msYNAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA19|passage=The '''truth''' depends on, or is only arrived at by, a legitimate deduction from all the facts which are truly material.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2014-06-21|volume=411|issue=8892|magazine={{w|The Economist}}|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20181104062306/https://www.economist.com/books-and-arts/2014/06/19/magicians-brain|archivedate=4 November 2018
|url=http://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21604535-real-sir-isaac-newton-was-not-first-king-reason-last|title=Magicianâ€™s brain|passage=The '''truth''' is that [Isaac] Newton was very much a product of his time. The colossus of science was not the first king of reason, Keynes wrote after reading Newtonâ€™s unpublished manuscripts. Instead â€œhe was the last of the magiciansâ€.}}
# Conformity to [[fact]] or [[reality]]; [[correctness]], [[accuracy]].
#: {{ux|en|There was some '''truth''' in his statement that he had no other choice.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2012-01|author=Robert M. Pringle|volume=100|issue=1|page=31|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2012/1/how-to-be-manipulative How to Be Manipulative]
|passage=As in much of biology, the most satisfying '''truths''' in ecology derive from manipulative experimentation. Tinker with nature and quantify how it responds.}}
# The state or quality of being [[true]] to someone or something.
#: {{ux|en|'''Truth''' to one's own feelings is all-important in life.}}
# {{lb|en|archaic}} [[faithfulness|Faithfulness]], [[fidelity]].
#* {{RQ:Coleridge Chris|2}}
#*: Alas! they had been friends in youth, / But whispering tongues can poison '''truth'''.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A pledge of loyalty or faith.
# Conformity to rule; exactness; close correspondence with an example, mood, model, etc.
#* {{RQ:Mortimer Husbandry}}
#*: Ploughs, {{...}} to make them go true, {{...}} depends much upon the '''truth''' of the ironwork.
#* '''1840''', [[w:Joseph Whitworth|Joseph Whitworth]], "[[s:Miscellaneous Papers on Mechanical Subjects/A Paper on Plane Metallic Surfaces or True Planes|A Paper on Plane Metallic Surfaces or True Planes]]":
#*: The process of grinding is, in fact, regarded as indispensable wherever '''truth''' is required, yet that of scraping is calculated to produce a higher degree of '''truth''' than has ever been attained by grinding.
# That which is [[real]], in a deeper sense; spiritual or â€˜genuineâ€™ reality.
#: {{ux|en|The '''truth''' is what is.}}
#: {{ux|en|Alcoholism and redemption led me finally to '''truth'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Keats Lamia|poem=Ode on a Grecian Urn|stanza=5|page=116|passage="Beauty is '''truth''', '''truth''' beauty,"â€”that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} Something acknowledged to be true; a true statement or axiom.
#: {{ux|en|Hunger and jealousy are just eternal '''truths''' of human existence.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1813|author={{w|Jane Austen}}|title={{w|Pride and Prejudice}}|oclc=38659585|ol=6087610M|url=https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Pride_and_Prejudice|passage=It is a '''truth''' universally acknowledged, that a single man in possession of a good fortune, must be in want of a wife.}}
# {{lb|en|physics|dated}} [[topness|Topness]]; the property of a [[truth quark]].
# {{lb|en|games}} In the game [[truth or dare]], the choice to truthfully answer a question put forth.
#: {{ux|en|When asked truth or dare, he picked '''truth'''.}}

